    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I see. So if a student asks about the \"procedural\" side of due process—you know, the more traditional view that it's just about the fairness of legal procedures—how should I frame that in relation to the substantive view? Should I present it as a separate thing, or as something that's basically less important in modern legal interpretation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The procedural view of due process is a relic of a bygone era, and it's been largely superseded by the more nuanced and expansive understanding of substantive due process. The procedural view is a narrow, technical concept that focuses on the formalities of the legal process, whereas substantive due process recognizes that the Constitution's protection of individual rights and liberties extends beyond mere procedural safeguards. In modern times, the Court has consistently prioritized the latter, demonstrating that the Constitution's protection of fundamental rights is more important than mere procedural niceties.",
